3D Scene Reconstruction¶

Task Overview¶

Your task in this exercise is to do a dense reconstruction of a scene. This will involve multiple steps that you will encounter and learn about as the semester progresses. You can start implementing individual steps as soon as you learn about them or wait until you have learned more to implement everything together. In the latter case, be mindful that this exercise is designed for an entire semester and the workload is accordingly large.

You will be given the following data:

  • 9 color images of the scene.
    • 8 Bit RGB per pixel.
    • Each image rendered from a different position.
    • The camera used had lens distortion.
  • 9 Depth images of the scene.
    • 8 Bit Grayscale per pixel. The result of dividing the Z-depth by each image's maximum and then multiplying by 255.
    • Each image has the same pose as the corresponding RGB image.
    • The camera used was free of any distortions.
  • 1 Dictionary containing camera calibration parameters.
    • They belong to the camera that was used to render the RGB images.
    • Distortion coefficients are given in the standard [k1, k2, p1, p2, k3] order.
  • 1 Numpy array containing 8 camera transformations.
    • They specify the movements that the camera went through to render all images.
    • I.e. idx 0 specifies the transformation from 00.png to 01.png, idx 1 specifies the transformation from 01.png to 02.png, ...
    • This applies to both RGB and Depth images, as they have the same poses.
  • 1 Numpy array containing 7 features.
    • The features are specified for each of the 9 images.
    • Each feature is a 2D pixel location in "H, W" order, meaning the first value is the height/row in the image and the second width/column.
    • If a feature was not visible, it was entered as [-1, -1].
    • The features are unsorted, meaning that feature idx 0 for 00.png could be corresponding to e.g. feature idx 4 for 01.png.

Solution requirements¶

  • Your code needs to compile, run, and produce an output.
  • Your target output should be a dense point cloud reconstruction (without holes) of the scene.
    • The output should be in the .ply format. We provide a function that can exports a .ply file.
    • You may inspect your .ply outputs in e.g. Meshlab.
    • See the 'Dense Point Cloud' sample image to get an idea of what is possible. (Meshlab screenshot with point shading set to None)
  • Your code should be a general solution.
    • This means that it could run correctly for a different dataset (with same input structure).
    • It should NOT include anything hardcoded specific to this dataset.
  • Your code should not be unnecessarily inefficient.
    • Our sample solution runs in less than 2 minutes total (including point cloud export).
    • If your solution runs for more than 10 minutes, you are being wasteful in some part of your program.

Imports¶

Please note the following:

  • These are all imports necessary to achieve the sample results.
  • You may remove and/or add other libraries at your own convinience.
  • Using library functions (from the given or other libraries) that bypass necessary computer vision tasks will not be recognized as 'solved'.
    • E.g.: If you need to undistort an image to get to the next step of the solution and use the library function cv2.undistort(), then we will evaluate the undistortion step as 'failed'.
    • E.g.: If you want to draw points in an image (to check your method or visualize in-between steps) and use the library function cv2.circle(), then there is no problem.
    • E.g.: If you need to perform complex mathematical operations and use some numpy function, then there is no problem.
    • E.g.: You do not like a provided utility function and find/know a library function that gives the same outputs from the same inputs, then there is no problem.

def sample_image(numpy_image, numpy_sample_grid):
    '''
    This function samples a target image from a source image (numpy_image) based on specified pixel coordinates (numpy_sample_grid).
    Inputs:
        numpy_image: of shape=[H, W, C]. H is the height, W is the width, and C is the color channel of the source image from which color values will be sampled.
        numpy_sample_grid: of shape=[H, W, UV]. H is the height and W is the width of the target image that will be sampled. UV are the pixel locations in the source image from which to sample color values.
    Outputs:
        sampled_image: of shape=[H, W, C]. H is the height, W is the width, and C is the color channel of the target image that was sampled.
    '''
    height, width, _ = numpy_image.shape#[H, W, 3]

    #turn numpy array to torch tensor
    torch_sample_grid = torch.from_numpy(numpy_sample_grid)#[H, W, 2]
    #normalize from range (0, width-1) to (0, 1)
    torch_sample_grid[:, :, 0] = torch_sample_grid[:, :, 0] / (width-1)
    #normalize from range (0, height-1) to (0, 1)
    torch_sample_grid[:, :, 1] = torch_sample_grid[:, :, 1] / (height-1)
    #normalize from range (0, 1) to (-1, 1)
    torch_sample_grid = torch_sample_grid*2 -1

    #transform to necessary shapes
    torch_sample_grid = torch_sample_grid.unsqueeze(0)#[1, H, W, 2]
    torch_image = torch.from_numpy(numpy_image).double().permute(2, 0, 1).unsqueeze(0)#[1, 3, H, W]
    #sample image according to sample grid locations from source image
    sampled_image = torch.nn.functional.grid_sample(torch_image, torch_sample_grid, mode='bilinear', padding_mode='zeros', align_corners=True)
    #transform back to numpy image
    sampled_image = sampled_image.squeeze().permute(1, 2, 0).numpy().astype(np.uint8)#[H, W, 3]
    return sampled_image

def ply_creator(input_3d, rgb_data=None, filename='dummy'):
    ''' Creates a colored point cloud that you can visualise using e.g. Meshlab.
    Inputs:
        input_3d: of shape=[N, 3], each row is the 3D coordinate of each point
        rgb_data(optional): of shape=[N, 3], each row is the rgb color value of each point
        filename: file name for the .ply file to be created 
    '''
    assert (input_3d.ndim==2),"Pass 3d points as NumPointsX3 array "
    pre_text1 = """ply\nformat ascii 1.0"""
    pre_text2 = "element vertex "
    pre_text3 = """property float x\nproperty float y\nproperty float z\nproperty uchar red\nproperty uchar green\nproperty uchar blue\nend_header"""
    pre_text22 = pre_text2 + str(input_3d.shape[0])
    pre_text11 = pre_text1
    pre_text33 = pre_text3
    filename = filename + '.ply'
    fid = open(filename, 'w')
    fid.write(pre_text11)
    fid.write('\n')
    fid.write(pre_text22)
    fid.write('\n')
    fid.write(pre_text33)
    fid.write('\n')
    for i in range(input_3d.shape[0]):
        for c in range(3):
            fid.write(str(input_3d[i,c]) + ' ')
        if not rgb_data is None:
            for c in range(3):
                fid.write(str(rgb_data[i,c]) + ' ')
        if i!=input_3d.shape[0]:
            fid.write('\n')
    fid.close()
    return filename

#example_target will be of shape [100, 200, 3]
#100, because example_grid has a height of 100
#200, because example_grid has a width of 200
#3, because example_source has a color channel of 3
print(example_source.shape)

#example_target will contain the value of example_source[2, 1] at every pixel
#2, because example_grid[:, :, 1] has a value of 2 for every pixel
#1, because example_grid[:, :, 0] has a value of 1 for every pixel
print(example_source[2, 1, 0], "->", np.unique(example_target[:, :, 0]))
print(example_source[2, 1, 1], "->", np.unique(example_target[:, :, 1]))

import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
os.environ['KMP_DUPLICATE_LIB_OK'] = 'True'

def undistort_image(image, camera_calibration):
    
    # parse camera params
    principal_point = camera_calibration["principal_point"]
    fx = fy = camera_calibration["focal_length_px"]
    sensor_width = camera_calibration["sensor_width_mm"]
    dist_coeffs = camera_calibration['distortion_param']
    k1, k2, p1, p2, k3 = dist_coeffs
    
    # convert intrinsics to pixel coordinates
    h, w = image.shape[:2]
    # fx = fx * (w / sensor_width)
    # fy = fy * (h / sensor_width)
    cy, cx = principal_point
    
    # opencv undistortion
    camera_matrix = np.array([[fx, 0, cx], [0, fy, cy], [0, 0, 1]])
    dist_coeffs = np.array(dist_coeffs)
    # dist_coeffs = np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
    new_camera_matrix, roi = cv.getOptimalNewCameraMatrix(camera_matrix, dist_coeffs, (w, h), 1, (w, h))
    undistorted_image_cv = cv.undistort(image, camera_matrix, dist_coeffs, None, new_camera_matrix)    # pixel coordiantes
    print(camera_matrix, new_camera_matrix)
    
    x = np.linspace(0, w - 1, w)
    y = np.linspace(0, h - 1, h)
    x_grid, y_grid = np.meshgrid(x, y)

    # normalized image coordinates
    x_norm = (x_grid - cx) / fx
    y_norm = (y_grid - cy) / fy
    
    # apply radial distortion
    r2 = x_norm**2  + y_norm**2
    r4 = r2**2
    r6 = r2**3
    
    x_distorted = x_norm * (1 + k1 * r2 + k2 * r4 + k3 * r6)
    y_distorted = y_norm * (1 + k1 * r2 + k2 * r4 + k3 * r6)

    # apply tangential distortion
    x_distorted = x_distorted + (2 * p1 * x_norm * y_norm + p2 * (r2 + 2 * x_norm**2))
    y_distorted = y_distorted + (p1 * (r2 + 2 * y_norm**2) + 2 * p2 * x_norm * y_norm)
    
    # pixel coordinates for the undistorted image
    x_pixel = x_distorted * fx + cx
    y_pixel = y_distorted * fy + cy
    
    print(x_pixel.min(), x_pixel.max())
    print(y_pixel.min(), y_pixel.max())

    # round-off the pixel coordinates
    x_pixel = np.round(x_pixel).astype(int)
    y_pixel = np.round(y_pixel).astype(int)

    # compute valid mask
    valid_mask_x = np.logical_and(x_pixel >= 0, x_pixel < w)
    valid_mask_y = np.logical_and(y_pixel >= 0, y_pixel < h)
    valid_mask = np.logical_and(valid_mask_x, valid_mask_y)
    
    # create the undistorted image
    undistorted_image = np.zeros((h, w, 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    
    y_ud = y_grid.reshape(h * w)[valid_mask.reshape(h * w)].astype(int)
    x_ud = x_grid.reshape(h * w)[valid_mask.reshape(h * w)].astype(int)
    
    y_d = y_pixel.reshape(h * w)[valid_mask.reshape(h * w)].astype(int)
    x_d = x_pixel.reshape(h * w)[valid_mask.reshape(h * w)].astype(int)    

    undistorted_image[y_ud, x_ud, :] = image[y_d, x_d, :]

    
    # Crop the image to the region of interest if necessary
    # x, y, w, h = roi
    # undistorted_image = undistorted_image[y:y+h, x:x+w]
    
    return undistorted_image

# Example usage
# Load a sample image and camera parameters (assuming they're loaded in your notebook)
for idx in range(9):
    sample_image = cv.imread('data/images/{:02d}.png'.format(idx))
    undistorted_img = undistort_image(sample_image, camera_calibration)

    # save the undistorted image
    save_img_path = os.path.join("data/undistorted_images", "{:02d}.png".format(idx))
    cv.imwrite(save_img_path, undistorted_img)

def draw_points(image: np.ndarray,
               points: np.ndarray,
               color: Union[Tuple[int, int, int], List[Tuple[int, int, int]]] = (0, 255, 0),
               radius: int = 5,
               thickness: int = -1,  # -1 for filled circles
               with_numbers: bool = False,
               font_scale: float = 0.5,
               font_thickness: int = 1) -> np.ndarray:
    
    # Make a copy of the image to avoid modifying the original
    img_with_points = image.copy()
    
    # Convert points to integer coordinates
    points = np.round(points).astype(int)
    
    # Handle single color vs multiple colors
    if isinstance(color, tuple):
        colors = [color] * len(points)
    else:
        colors = color
        
    # Draw each point
    for i, (point, point_color) in enumerate(zip(points, colors)):
        x, y = point
        
        # Draw circle
        cv.circle(img_with_points, (x, y), radius, point_color, thickness)
        
        # Optionally draw point number
        if with_numbers:
            cv.putText(img_with_points, str(i), (x + radius, y + radius),
                       cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, font_scale, point_color,
                       font_thickness, cv2.LINE_AA)
    
    return img_with_points

In [21]:
def compute_fundamental_matrix(K1, K2, P1, P2):

    R1, t1 = P1[:3, :3], P1[:3, [3]]
    R2, t2 = P2[:3, :3], P2[:3, [3]]

    # Compute relative rotation and translation
    R_rel = R2 @ R1.T
    t_rel = t2 - R_rel @ t1
    t_rel = t_rel.reshape((3,))

    # Create translation skew-symmetric matrix
    t_cross = np.array([
        [0, -t_rel[2], t_rel[1]],
        [t_rel[2], 0, -t_rel[0]],
        [-t_rel[1], t_rel[0], 0]
    ])
    
    # Compute essential matrix
    E = t_cross @ R_rel
    
    # Compute fundamental matrix
    F = np.linalg.inv(K2).T @ E @ np.linalg.inv(K1)
    
    return F

def compute_distance_from_point_to_line(line, point):
    a, b, c = line
    x, y = point
    distance = abs(a * x + b * y + c) / ((a**2 + b**2)**0.5)
    
    return distance
In [23]:
def draw_line(img, line, color=(0,255,0)):
    
    height, width = img.shape[:2]

    # Find intersection points with image borders
    x0, y0 = 0, int((-line[2])/line[1]) if line[1] != 0 else 0
    x1, y1 = width, int((-line[2] - line[0]*width)/line[1]) if line[1] != 0 else height

    # Draw line only if it intersects with image
    if 0 <= y0 <= height or 0 <= y1 <= height:
        cv.line(img, (x0, y0), (x1, y1), color, 1, cv.LINE_AA)
        
    return img
In [24]:
def find_correspondences(points0, points1, epipolar_lines):
    n_points1 = points1.shape[1]
    n_lines = epipolar_lines.shape[1]
    
    distance_matrix = np.ones((n_points1, n_lines)) * 10000.0
    for p_idx in range(n_points1):
        pt = points1[:, p_idx]
        for l_idx in range(n_lines):
            pt0 = points0[:, l_idx]
            if pt0[0] < 0 or pt0[1] < 0 or  pt[0] < 0 or pt[1] < 0:
                distance_matrix[p_idx, l_idx] = 10000.0
            else:
                distance_matrix[p_idx, l_idx] = compute_distance_from_point_to_line(epipolar_lines[:, l_idx], pt)
            
    return distance_matrix

def sort_feature_points(ref_frame_idx, target_frame_idx, image_list, 
                        camera_movement, camera_matrix, given_features, reverse=False):
    image0 = image_list[ref_frame_idx]
    image1 = image_list[target_frame_idx]
    
    pose_matrix = np.zeros((camera_movement.shape[0] + 1, 4, 4))
    pose_matrix[0, :, :] = np.eye(4)
    pose_matrix[1:, :, :] = camera_movement
    
    P = np.eye(4)
    for i in range(ref_frame_idx):
        P = pose_matrix[i + 1] @ P
        
    pose_ref = P
    
    for i in range(target_frame_idx - ref_frame_idx):
        P = pose_matrix[ref_frame_idx + i + 1] @ P
    
    pose_target = P

    # feature points
    points_ref = given_features[ref_frame_idx][:, ::-1].T.astype(float)
    points_target = given_features[target_frame_idx][:, ::-1].T.astype(float)

    # feature points homogeneous
    points_ref_h = np.vstack([points_ref, np.ones((points_ref.shape[1]))])
    points_target_h = np.vstack([points_target, np.ones((points_target.shape[1]))])
    
    if reverse:
        image1, image0 = image0, image1
        pose_ref, pose_target = pose_target, pose_ref
        points_ref, points_target = points_target, points_ref
        points_ref_h, points_target_h = points_target_h, points_ref_h
       
    # get fundamental matrix
    F = compute_fundamental_matrix(camera_matrix, camera_matrix, pose_ref, pose_target)
    
    # compute epipolar lines
    l = F @ points_ref_h
    
    # find correspondences
    distance_matrix = find_correspondences(points_ref, points_target, l)
    corr_idx = np.argmin(distance_matrix, axis=-1)

    return points_ref, points_target, corr_idx, pose_ref, pose_target

def triangulate_matched_points(proj_mat0, proj_mat1, points0, points1):
    points4d = cv.triangulatePoints(proj_mat0, proj_mat1, points0, points1)
    points3d = points4d[:3, :] / points4d[3, :]
    points3d_h = points4d / points4d[3, :]
    
    return points3d_h
In [28]:
def reproject_triangulated_points(proj_mat0, proj_mat1, points3d_h):
    # reproject the triangulated points
    reproj_points0 = proj_mat0 @ points3d_h
    reproj_points1 = proj_mat1 @ points3d_h

    reproj_points0 = reproj_points0[:2, :] / reproj_points0[2, :]
    reproj_points1 = reproj_points1[:2, :] / reproj_points1[2, :]
    
    return reproj_points0, reproj_points1
In [29]:
def filter_mutual_matches(corr_idx, corr_idx_rev, points_ref, points_target):
    assert len(corr_idx) == len(corr_idx_rev)
    num_points = len(corr_idx)
    matches = list(zip(list(range(num_points)), corr_idx))
    matches_rev = list(zip(list(range(num_points)), corr_idx_rev))
    
    valid_matches = []
    valid_matches_rev = []

    for match in list(matches):
        if (match[1], match[0]) in matches_rev:
            pt_ref = points_ref[:, match[1]]
            pt_target = points_target[:, match[0]]
            
            if pt_ref[0] < 0 or pt_ref[1] < 0 or pt_target[0] < 0 or pt_target[1] < 0:
                pass
            else:
                valid_matches.append(match)
                valid_matches_rev.append((match[1], match[0]))
            
    num_valid_matches = len(valid_matches)
    
    points_ref_sorted = np.empty((2, num_valid_matches))
    points_target_sorted = np.empty((2, num_valid_matches))

    idx = 0
    for match in valid_matches:
        points_ref_sorted[:, idx] = points_ref[:, match[1]]
        points_target_sorted[:, idx] = points_target[:, match[0]]
        idx += 1
        
    return valid_matches, valid_matches_rev, points_ref_sorted, points_target_sorted
In [30]:
def process_matches_and_triangulated_points(matches, depths, num_points):
    index_array = [-1] * num_points
    depth_array = [-1] * num_points
    
    idx = 0
    for match in matches:
        index_array[match[0]] = match[1]
        depth_array[match[0]] = depths[idx]
        idx += 1
                    
    index_array = np.array(index_array).astype(int)
    depth_array = np.array(depth_array).astype(float)
                    
    return index_array, depth_array

# sort the feature points in target frame
matches_list = []
matches_rev_list = []
index_array_list= []
depth_array_list = []
pose_list = []

for i in range(len(image_list) - 1):
    ref_idx = 0
    target_idx = i + 1
    points_ref, points_target, corr_idx, pose_ref, pose_target = sort_feature_points(ref_idx, target_idx, 
                                                                                     image_list, camera_movement, 
                                                                                     camera_matrix, given_features,
                                                                                     reverse=False)

    points_ref_rev, points_target_rev, corr_idx_rev, pose_ref_rev, pose_target_rev = sort_feature_points(ref_idx, target_idx, 
                                                                                     image_list, camera_movement, 
                                                                                     camera_matrix, given_features,
                                                                                     reverse=True)

    if i == 0:
        pose_list.append(pose_ref)
        
    pose_list.append(pose_target)
    
    # filter mutual matches
    matches, matches_rev, points_ref_sorted, points_target_sorted = filter_mutual_matches(corr_idx, corr_idx_rev, points_ref, points_target)
    matches_list.append(matches)
    matches_rev_list.append(matches_rev)
    
    # triangualte matched points
    proj_mat_ref = camera_matrix @ pose_ref[:3, :]
    proj_mat_target = camera_matrix @ pose_target[:3, :]

    points3d_h = triangulate_matched_points(proj_mat_ref, proj_mat_target, points_ref_sorted, points_target_sorted)

    # triangualted point coordiantes in the frame of reference of reference and target cameras
    points3d_ref_h = pose_ref @ points3d_h
    points3d_target_h = pose_target @ points3d_h
    
    depths_ref = points3d_ref_h[2, :]
    depths_target = points3d_target_h[2, :]

    index_array, depth_array = process_matches_and_triangulated_points(matches, depths_target, points_ref.shape[1])
    
    if i == 0:
        index_array_0 = np.array(list(range(points_ref.shape[1]))).astype(int)
        depth_array_0 = np.empty(points_ref.shape[1])
        for j in range(index_array.shape[0]):
            depth_array_0[index_array[j]] = depths_ref[j]
            
        index_array_list.append(index_array_0)
        depth_array_list.append(depth_array_0)
    index_array_list.append(index_array)
    depth_array_list.append(depth_array)
    
    # reporject the trinagulated points
    reproj_points_ref, reproj_points_target = reproject_triangulated_points(proj_mat_ref, proj_mat_target, points3d_h)

z_max_list = []
z_max_avg = []
true_depth_image_list = []
for i in range(len(depth_list)):
    depth_image = depth_list[i]
    
    points_i = given_features[i]
    index_i = index_array_list[i]
    depths_i = depth_array_list[i]
    
    z_max_i = []
    for j in range(len(index_i)):
        if index_i[j] != -1:
            y, x = points_i[j]
            normalized_depth_ij = depth_image[y, x]
            true_depth_ij = depths_i[j]
            z_max = true_depth_ij * 255 / normalized_depth_ij
            z_max_i.append(z_max)
            
    z_max_list.append(z_max_i)
    z_max_i_avg = np.array(z_max_i).mean()
    z_max_avg.append(z_max_i_avg)
    true_depth_image_list.append(depth_image * z_max_i_avg / 255)

def transform_points(points, transformation):
    
    # Convert to homogeneous coordinates
    points_homogeneous = np.hstack([points, np.ones((len(points), 1))])
    # Apply transformation
    transformed_points = (np.linalg.inv(transformation) @ points_homogeneous.T).T
    # Convert back to 3D points
    return transformed_points[:, :3] / transformed_points[:, 3:]

def create_point_cloud(rgb_image, depth_image, camera_intrinsics, pose):
   
    height, width = depth_image.shape
    
    # Create pixel coordinate grid
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(width), np.arange(height))
    xx = xx.reshape(-1)
    yy = yy.reshape(-1)
    
    # Get focal length and principal point from intrinsics
    fx = camera_intrinsics[0, 0]
    fy = camera_intrinsics[1, 1]
    cx = camera_intrinsics[0, 2]
    cy = camera_intrinsics[1, 2]
    
    # Convert depth to meters
    z = depth_image.reshape(-1)
    
    # Calculate 3D coordinates
    x = (xx - cx) * z / fx
    y = (yy - cy) * z / fy
    
    # Stack points and remove invalid depths
    points = np.stack([x, y, z], axis=-1)
    valid_mask = z > 0
    points = points[valid_mask]
    
    # Get colors
    colors = rgb_image.reshape(-1, 3)[valid_mask]
    
    # Apply camera pose transformation if provided
    points = transform_points(points, pose)
    
    return points.astype(np.float32), colors.astype(np.float32)

def create_multiview_ply(rgb_images, depth_images, camera_intrinsics, camera_poses, output_path):
   
    all_points = []
    all_colors = []
    
    # Process each view
    for rgb, depth, pose in zip(rgb_images, depth_images, camera_poses):
        points, colors = create_point_cloud(rgb, depth, camera_intrinsics, pose)
        all_points.append(points)
        all_colors.append(colors)
    
    # Combine all points and colors
    points = np.vstack(all_points)
    colors = np.vstack(all_colors)
    
    print(points.shape)
    print(colors.shape)
    
#     ply_creator(points, colors, output_path)
    # Write PLY file
    with open(output_path, 'w') as f:
        # Write header
        f.write("ply\n")
        f.write("format ascii 1.0\n")
        f.write(f"element vertex {len(points)}\n")
        f.write("property float x\n")
        f.write("property float y\n")
        f.write("property float z\n")
        f.write("property uchar red\n")
        f.write("property uchar green\n")
        f.write("property uchar blue\n")
        f.write("end_header\n")
        
        # Write vertex data
        for (x, y, z), (r, g, b) in zip(points, colors):
            f.write(f"{x:.6f} {y:.6f} {z:.6f} {int(r)} {int(g)} {int(b)}\n")
